1.)¶

To investigate the influence of temperature and humidity on this process, the time to decay was measured for 18 slices of white bread, which were placed in 3 different environments and humidified or not. The data are given in the file bread.txt, with the first column time to decay in hours, the second column the environment (cold, warm or intermediate temperature) and the third column the humidity.

In [1]:
bread = read.table("bread.txt",header=TRUE)
bread$humidity = as.factor(bread$humidity)
bread$environment = as.factor(bread$environment);attach(bread)

  • $n=18$ total observations, $I=3$ levels of factor A (env), $J=2$ levels of factor B (hum), i.e $N = \frac{n}{I\times J} = \frac{18}{3\times 2} = 3$ obervations per combination.

a) The 18 slices came from a single loaf, but were randomized to the 6 combinations of conditions. Present an R-code for this randomization process.

I=3; J=2; N=3
rbind(rep(1:I,each=N*J),rep(1:J,N*I),sample(1:(N*I*J)))

The returned matrix can be interpreted as a list of randomized tuples, i.e : $(l_A, l_B, i)$, e.g the first column represents $(1,1,18)$, meaning observation 18 is assigned level 1 of factor A and level 1 of factor B.

b) Make two boxplots of hours versus the two factors and two interaction plots (keeping the two factors fixed in turn)

In [7]:
par(mfrow=c(1,4));options(repr.plot.width=15, repr.plot.height=4)
boxplot(hours~humidity);boxplot(hours~environment);
interaction.plot(humidity,environment,hours);interaction.plot(environment,humidity,hours);

We can expect significant interactions, since the non-parallelity connot be only due to noise.

c)Perform an analysis of variance to test for effect of the factors temperature, humidity, and their interaction. Describe the interaction effect in words.

In [22]:
model = lm(hours~humidity*environment)
round(drop1(model, test="F"),3)

Testing $H0 : \gamma_{i,j} = 0 \ \forall \ (i,j)$ has a very small p-value (=rejected) so we can say that there is significant evidence for interaction. As an example, for warm and intermediate environments, wet humidites will decrease the mean hours, while for a cold environment, a wet humidity will actaully increase the hours.

For testing the two factors specifically, we use the additive model (Since the design is balanced, we dont need to worry about formulae order).

d.) Which of the two factors has the greatest (numerical) influence on the decay? Is this a good question?

According to the output of the additive anova, environment has a greater effect than humidity. The question may not be too interesting considering the significant interactions and it's influence on the response. A better question might be which combination has the strongest effect. Looking at single factors and determining its numerical effect without treating interactions will yield unreasonable results.

d) Perform the Friedman test to test whether there is an effect of interface.

In [55]:
friedman.test(y=time,groups=interface,blocks=skill)

	Friedman rank sum test

data:  time, interface and skill
Friedman chi-squared = 6.4, df = 2, p-value = 0.04076

The friedman test (the rank-based alternative to ANOVA) tests the null hypothesis that apart from an effect of blocks, the location parameter of y is the same in each of the groups. $H_0 : \alpha_1 = \alpha_2 = \alpha_3 = 0$ is therefore rejected ($p = 0.04076$).

If we simply omit the blocking factor, the linear model will incorporate any variance which is produced by the blocking factor into the treatment factor. This will give false estimates since now the treatment factors incorporate variance that does not belong to it. By using a blocking factor we can explain parts of the variance by this blocking factor, which ultimatively allows us to make more precise conclusions about the factor of itnerest.

Using a random effects model we essentially assume that the blocks (here cows) are not fixed and therefore limited to the sample, but rather randomly drawn from a distribution of cows, the block population. The full model yields a block population estimate of $\mathcal{N}(0, 133.145)$ (individual effects) Estimated treatment and period effects stay the same as in fixed effects.

Refitting a reduced model (without treatment) and comparing it to the full model will give us the actual treatment effect.

In [71]:
me_model_full = lmer(milk~treatment+order+per+(1|id),REML=FALSE);
me_model_reduced = lmer(milk~order+per+(1|id),REML=FALSE)
anova(me_model_full, me_model_reduced)

<dbl><dbl><dbl><dbl><dbl><dbl><dbl><dbl>

Comparing both models yields the indication that the treatment factor does not have a significant effect, since $H_0$ cannot be rejected. Essentially this means that the larger model does not add much "explanatory power" (i.e explained variance) to the reduced model. If we compare that with the outcome of the fixed effects model, we get the same conclusion.

a)

Altough both test are technically executed in an equivalent way, more appropiate here is a test for homogenity ($H_0$), meaning the proportions of the levels are approximately equal. Since we want to compare writing styles we are particularly interested in looking at the word distributions and if/how they are determined by the book and author. Using $E_{i,j} = n*p_{i,j}*p_j = n* \frac{n_{i}}{n}*\frac{n_{j}}{n} = \frac{n_{i}*n_{j}}{n}$, we can evaluate $H_0$ based on $\sum_{j=1}^{J} \frac{\left(n_{i j}-E_{i j}\right)^{2}}{E_{i j}} \sim \chi_{(1-1)(J-1)}^{2}$

b) Using the given data set, investigate whether Austen herself was consistent in her different novels. Where are the main inconsistencies?

The plots give us an overview of the different values as well as the most extreme 3 values per plot. The observations of 5, 8, 15 and 44 are marked. Ordering the absolute values of the residuals, from smallest to largest, also gives us the numbers 5, 15 and 8 having the largest value. To further see if these leverage points are an influence point we can compute the Cook’s distances.

In [99]:
plot(cooks.distance(model), type="b")

We can see the four deviating points clearly in the graph. For Cook’s distance we consider a datapoint influential when the distance is larger than 1, so in this case 5, 8, 35 and 44. We will remove these points from the data set as they potentially overshadow the “real” data that can provide us with more insights on general behaviour.

In [100]:
df = df[-c(5,8,35,44),];attach(df)

Two more iterations yield the final model according to the step down method. (Bad and Pop were iteratively eliminated (p > 0.05) ). The model estimated : Expend = -110.659 + 0.02971145 Employ + 0.02686229 Lawyers + Error

Conclusion : We choose the simpler model not only because simpler models are prefered in general, but also because we know that the covariates of the second model are highly colinear.

The residuals are centered around 0, and look roughly equally distributed (Although we see the outliers mentioned earlier). The quasi-structure within the residuals distribution is generally not desirable. The QQplot also indicates non-normality, but also partly due to the previously identified outliers. The scatter plot show a clear linear relationship between the covariate and the response, but they also show (again) the outliers. All in all the model is simply relatively robust.
